          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Which inherited disorder results from a",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which inherited disorder results from a defective ATP7B transporter, leading to copper accumulation in the liver, brain, and cornea?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Menkes disease</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Menkes disease involves defective copper absorption, not accumulation. It is X-linked and leads to copper deficiency with kinky hair and connective tissue problems.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Wilson disease</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Wilson disease results from a defective ATP7B transporter, preventing copper excretion in bile and incorporation into caeruloplasmin, causing toxic copper build-up.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Acrodermatitis enteropathica</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Acrodermatitis enteropathica is a genetic disorder of zinc absorption, not copper metabolism.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Haemochromatosis</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Haemochromatosis involves iron overload due to defective hepcidin regulation, not copper accumulation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Wilson disease is caused by defective ATP7B, which normally exports copper into bile and loads it onto caeruloplasmin. Without it, copper accumulates in tissues."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. Wilson disease is the classic copper overload disorder caused by ATP7B mutations, with Kayser-Fleischer rings as the hallmark sign."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
