          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which of the following is the earliest electrocardiographic change seen in hyperkalaemia?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Widened QRS complexes</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Widened QRS complexes occur at a later stage, after peaked T waves have already appeared, reflecting slowed ventricular conduction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Peaked T waves</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Peaked T waves are the earliest ECG sign of hyperkalaemia, caused by accelerated repolarisation due to high extracellular potassium.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sine-wave pattern</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The sine-wave pattern is a pre-terminal finding indicating imminent cardiac arrest. It appears after peaked T waves and widened QRS complexes.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Prolonged PR interval</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>PR prolongation can occur in hyperkalaemia but appears after peaked T waves. The classic sequence is: peaked T waves → wide QRS → sine wave → cardiac arrest.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "Remember the hyperkalaemia ECG sequence: peaked T waves appear first, followed by widened QRS complexes, then a sine-wave pattern, and finally cardiac arrest."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The ECG progression in hyperkalaemia follows a predictable sequence: peaked T waves → widened QRS → sine wave → cardiac arrest."
                }
              ],
