          "label": "<p>Knowledge check</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Which buffer system is the most importan",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which buffer system is the most important extracellular buffer in blood?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Phosphate buffer system</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The phosphate buffer operates mainly inside cells and in urine (pKa 6.8). It is not the principal extracellular buffer.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Bicarbonate buffer system</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The bicarbonate buffer is the most important extracellular buffer. It is regulated by both the lungs (CO₂ excretion) and kidneys (HCO₃⁻ reabsorption).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Haemoglobin buffer system</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Haemoglobin is a powerful buffer but operates inside red blood cells (intracellular), not in the extracellular fluid.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Albumin buffer system</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Albumin contributes to protein buffering but is far less significant than the bicarbonate system in extracellular fluid.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The bicarbonate buffer system is the most important extracellular buffer. H⁺ + HCO₃⁻ ⇌ H₂CO₃ ⇌ H₂O + CO₂. The lungs control CO₂ and the kidneys control HCO₃⁻."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done. The bicarbonate buffer system is the principal extracellular buffer, described by the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = 6.1 + log([HCO₃⁻] / [dissolved CO₂])."
                }
              ],
